steps:
We find the prime factorizations of the two numbers: \begin{align*}
315&=3^2\cdot5\cdot7,\\
108&=2^2\cdot3^3.
\end{align*}

The only common prime factor is $3$; the minimum exponent of $3$ is $2$, so the GCD is $3^2=\boxed{9}$.

According to the standard order of operations, division occurs before subtraction. We find that our answer is \begin{align*}
8-4 \div 2 - 1 &= 8-2-1 \\
&= 6-1 \\
&= \boxed{5}.
\end{align*}

Notice that the two fractions have the same denominator, so we can add them. Addition is commutative, so we can rearrange the terms to get  \begin{align*}
\frac{k-3}{2} +\frac{3k+1}{2}+3k+1 &=\frac{4k-2}{2}+3k+1 \\
&=2k-1+3k+1 \\
&=\boxed{5k}.\end{align*}

